Clinton and Trump &apos;s economic policies compared : it &apos;s all about the money
investing in infrastructure and preventing the TTP trade agreement - both Clinton and Trump want it .
however , the two US presidential candidates are divided on fiscal and energy policy and on a fundamental issue .
the differences in economic policy between Donald Trump and Hillary Clinton are based on a more fundamental and philosophical difference .
the , about the role of the state .
Trump wants to keep that in doubt rather small and warns about how the state can hurt the economy - with taxes and regulations .
Clinton wants to steer the economy to death and regulate to death , he says .
he himself would be very different , Trump claims .
he will see regulations go back massively , and he is pushing for sweeping tax reform with lower tax rates - for private individuals and for businesses .
Clinton , by contrast , says the state has certain tasks to do , he has disadvantaged opportunities and needs money for that .
that &apos;s why taxes would be increased for the rich , she says .
interestingly , both are very close to infrastructure .
this must be invested , Trump and Clinton say almost the same thing .
the Democratic candidate announces even the biggest investment in new jobs since World War II .
government investment programs in infrastructure are classic democratic policies and are strongly opposed , for example , by the state @-@ run Teaparty wing of Republicans .
so Trump could still have partisan discussions .
the differences in energy and climate policy are clearer .
Trump wants to build coal @-@ fired power plants and drive coal production back into the US .
oil production is also expected to be possible in previously protected areas , and the Paris Climate Change Agreement aims to terminate it .
Clinton , by contrast , explicitly wants to expand renewable energy with her investment program and calls for &quot; a country will become the superpower of clean energy and create millions of jobs . &quot;
&quot; it will probably be either China , Germany or America - I want us to be . &quot;
but not only in infrastructure - even in international trade agreements , the two competitors are not too far apart .
TPP , the Trans @-@ Pacific trade agreement , both do not want to sign .
at the same time , however , both do not want to isolate the US from international trade - but simply to better protect American jobs .
they should then be paid better , say , Clinton .
the current minimum wage of $ 7.25 is a hunger wage .
he wants to raise it to $ 15 an hour .
what Trump wants to do on this issue is not entirely clear : once he says that the minimum wage has to go out , he says he cannot be changed .
but the big discussion of the coming months is likely to be more about the fiscal policies of the two camps .
on the one hand , Trump , who wants to relieve the economy and citizens to boost growth .
his critics maintain that this would only increase the budget deficit .
on the other hand , Clinton , who at least wants to demand from the rich that they pay more taxes , and whose critics say : more taxes are not the solution either .
escape : &apos; every fled woman has experience of sexual violence &apos;
sexual violence is almost part of everyday life for women fleeing alone .
when they arrive in Germany , they are often traumatised .
a house offers refuge .
four women sit in a large kitchen .
each has a baby at most one year old .
one put her little son in the arm .
he looks curious in the room with big eyes .
his mother stares at the table plate .
until she realizes she is being watched .
she smiles briefly and kisses the little ones .
the scene acts normally .
until you talk to Katrin Bahr .
she is a division manager of Condrobs , a provider of social assistance services in Bavaria , and is also involved in the issue of women fleeing .
the four women in the kitchen are fled .
they live in Munich &apos;s north in one of the few decentralized shelters for single women and their children in Bavaria .
in January , Condrobs established the facility along with Pro Familia and the Munich Women &apos;s Aid .
it has recently been officially opened .
sixty people live there - about 40 women and 20 children .
men don &apos;t exist - nor as visitors .
the exception is a watchman on the door .
&quot; it &apos;s not exaggerated to say : every woman who arrives here has had experience of sexual violence on her flight , &quot; says Bahr .
&quot; men flee because of wars because they are persecuted politically because they face torture or death or because their families send them to Europe as a means of hope , &quot; she told them .
for women , other reasons for the flight outweigh : &quot; many are secretly stealing it because they see no other way out . &quot;
in their homeland , they have made experience of sexual violence , forced marriages , honour killings , slavery or forced prostitution .
it continues .
on the run , that continues .
&quot; the fact that Schlepper , for example , calls for a bottle of water a sexual act is not a rarity , &quot; says Bahr .
and women are alone , they are not protected by their families .
who believes that the end , once they arrive in Germany , is mistaken , tells Bahr .
even here , single women in refugee shelters would often be seen as inferior and at worst abused .
as a result , about 90 percent of women living in accommodation in Munich &apos;s north are traumatised , she estimates .
&quot; some of the children certainly haven &apos;t been voluntary . &quot;
many women are so used to saying nothing .
&quot; or they don &apos;t trust to speak openly about the experience because the shame is too big . &quot;
as they often don &apos;t help , it takes more accommodation only for them , demands Bahr .
in Bavaria , the seven district governments are responsible for housing refugees .
the question of whether they knew about a project similar to that in Munich , some answer no .
in Oberpfalz and Oberfranken , for example , there is no such thing in government accommodation .
even in Swabia , women alone are not housed separately , says Karl @-@ Heinz Meyer , press secretary of the government .
in Oberbayern , Unter- und Mittelfranken there are floors or own houses in some community accommodation only for single women and their children .
the exception is Niederbayern , where there are two central accommodation exclusively for women .
the Committee on Women &apos;s Rights and Gender Equality also calls for women to be accommodated separately from men .
in a study published for the committee , it said : &quot; it is very important for men and women to be housed separately . &quot;
&quot; if privacy is missing or if men and women are housed together , violence against women can occur - continuously - . &quot;
in particular , washing rooms should be separated and easily accessible to women , the study states .
how much women feel about this need for protection can be read on the journey to the house in Munich .
&quot; since getting around that it gives us , we have a long waiting list , &quot; says Bahr .
you could easily make up a second house .
