PokÃ©mon Go , a hunt for health and happiness that is worth it
it is fascinating to see how the world is changing .
the fact that teenagers and children no longer go out to play but rather prefer to spend their spare time staring at screens has been lamented by many over the last decade .
Pokemon Go is about getting people off the sofa and getting more active .
time on screen was initially on TV , then limited to video games and most recently to smartphones .
so it &apos;s great to see that technology and outdoor activities are not mutually exclusive .
I am referring , of course , to the PokÃ©mon Go @-@ Wahn , an app based on the characters that were first created for video games in the 1990s ( later created a cartoon series , game cards and other spin @-@ offs ) .
like many phenomena of pop culture , interest fell somewhat ahead of the release of the game in the US , Australia and New Zealand in early July .
market entry in other countries has been postponed by the massive demand that overloaded the servers .
within days , PokÃ©mon Go had more users than tinder and almost as many as Twitter .
how does it work ?
in short , players go out with their smartphones and look for PokÃ©mons to be tracked with a GPS and , once found , &quot; photographed &quot; ( via a screenshot on the phone ) or &quot; captured . &quot;
a generation that played the game when it was even younger joined the polls and jumped for the search from the sofa .
in the US , the game led to a significant increase in steps that the &quot; average &quot; person resets every day .
Cardiogram , an app for Apple Watch that tracked 35,000 users , told The Washington Post recently that within two days of market launch of the game , the number of tracked people training 30 minutes each day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent .
the company does not know who plays PokÃ©mon Go - it only sees the raw data for performance improvement .
many public awareness campaigns on health that people want to &quot; take 30 minutes of time , &quot; &quot; get off the sofa &quot; and &quot; be active every day &quot; encountered deaf ears because many public messages about health are boring and come from people who look elastic .
yet the importance of sport cannot be overstated .
those who regularly drive sport reduce their chances of contracting cancer or depression .
physical activity helps with weight control , high blood pressure , diabetes and a long list of benefits that is too long to lead them here .
but the miracle of PokÃ©mon Go is that it will get people to do something outdoors that makes them fun .
three pillars of health are covered - movement , fresh air and sunshine and fun .
some people even close new friendships in the hunt .
as always , there are mural playmakers who always have to complain about something .
and yes , someone could run against a door .
what &apos;s it ?
a breakthrough has occurred .
even though smartphone apps like Fitbit have been able to track down our activity earlier , they gave us no reason to do sport as this game does .
the new will lose its appeal and the use will wane over time .
however , due to Pokemon &apos;s success , there will be more games that will combine apps and virtual reality with activism in the real world , helping many people hunt to be more active , fitter and healthier .
