destination plates : who actually buys records ?
lonely middle @-@ aged men love plates .
before you rush to the comment part to oversaw it under the pseudonym non @-@ Allevenus men &apos;s middle age with rough insults , this statement derives from current data .
according to YouGov , the much @-@ vaunted revival of records is not due to a boom in millennials who want to welcome the novelty of physical objects , but to midlife nostalgia .
those who recently bought a plate are all predictably aged between 45 and 54 .
in fact , the age group of 18 @-@ 24 is the most unlikely buyer group .
it &apos;s also no hordes by amateur collectors - it has an emotional meaning : older record buyers retain their feelings more for themselves ( 56 % vs. 53 % ) and enjoy spending time alone ( 69 % vs. 66 % ) .
but are YouGov &apos;s results true ?
if this blog were a news report on television , the camera would follow me while I run in the middle of a busy street in Soho , wear a modest gray suit and walk wildly before I stand , keep my hands and say something defining as : &quot; so let &apos;s take a closer look at it . &quot;
so let &apos;s take a look at it .
even though the heart of Sohos is slowly bowing to its charm - hotels , restaurants and offices now fill the buildings where once independent sellers were based - there is still a handful of fantastic plate specials .
I would probably ask the cameraman to turn off the camera for the next part , where I am close to different men in such shops and try to assess their age and mood through observation .
Stuart from Glasgow , 55 , whom I am joined by Sister Ray ( data number : two young women , three middle @-@ aged men ) in Reckless Records ( data number : eight middle @-@ aged men , one woman , presumably around the 20 ) , is one day because of a meeting in London and goes through the shops to fill the couple of hours .
is he a collector , I ask ?
&quot; I appreciate already , &quot; he says .
I have about 3,000 or 4,000 records .
these records , depicted above ( he sent me the snapshot by email , I didn &apos;t follow him home ) , dress up the walls of his apartment room .
the reason he owns such a considerable number of albums and singles is the result of his disposable income : he is now able to buy records he could not afford when they appeared and again buy items he sold when he was young and bankrupt .
&quot; a lot of things I buy are from the late 1960s , early 70s , which appeared when I was 11 or 12 ... things where I was probably something too young to buy them , &quot; he says .
he agrees that those who buy records are more introverted and like to spend time alone , adding : &quot; I don &apos;t smoke and I don &apos;t drink very much .
that &apos;s my lads .
WEZ , 25 , who works at Sister Ray , also believes that many customers he meets will reach the YouGov profile .
however , he has also noticed a new wave of people being influenced by the media boot , people who have heard about the comeback and are being prompted to buy their old plates again .
of the conversations I have had , people usually got rid of their collection by 1998 or 1999 .
customers who once sold their plates to buy CDs now sell their CDs to buy their plates again , &quot; he says .
that would explain the boom to supporters of the record revival of a certain age .
but what about the alleged emotional significance of records ?
it takes only a few seconds in a business like Phonica to realize that record stores offer a reassuring community of like @-@ minded people .
according to Wez , some of the older customers took advantage of the contactless payment system .
some record fans feel overwhelmed by the digital world and want to retreat to the stability of familiar disk hulls , from items that alert happy youth events .
&quot; I think sometimes it can be filling a void or owning material possessions as a kind of consolation , &quot; says Wez .
this is the case with me as a collector and I think it &apos;s the case with many people .
it &apos;s an easy way to get mentally involved .
&quot; we &apos;re like their social workers ! &quot; flares an employee from a plate stack .
a survey by the ICM in April revealed that nearly 50 % of people who bought a record last month have not yet heard it .
the survey also found that 41 % own a record player they never use , while 7 % of those buying a record do not own a record player .
at this time of the news report , I would probably be very concerned , while I blew through a stack of Bossa Nova complications .
Jonny , 42 , who works on sounds of the Universe ( data number : three middle @-@ aged men ) , noticed a &quot; trophy aspect &quot; of the revival .
&quot; someone came here just recently and said , &quot; I don &apos;t own a record player , but I &apos;d like to buy a Radiohead sound plate so I can put them on the shelf , &quot; he says .
this is not a big percentage , but it definitely happens .
more productive , less music @-@ like .
we have people who say , &quot; I don &apos;t have a record player . &quot;
these are younger people , not older ones , who are slow to get in .
Fopp , which devoted almost an entire floor to the records , has a bare audience when I go in .
there are couples around the 70 , tourists taking photos , teens and middle @-@ aged women .
even though the atmosphere is slightly less relaxed than in the aforementioned shops - Wild Beasts of the newest synthesizer and sex @-@ packed pop instead of experimental jazz drenched from the loudspeakers - it is good to see such diversity among customers .
none of them look very lonely , but naming mental trauma is hard to detect when standing next to someone for 30 seconds .
Elanora , 27 , has been running around in the business for a few minutes and looks at the variety of plates for sale .
it makes more of a shop bump than a big one .
it doesn &apos;t deserve much , so collecting records is not a real option , she says .
it costs a lot .
it &apos;s easy to hear music from a computer or in other ways , but the beauty of plates is ... &quot; it drives away with a beloved sigh .
I don &apos;t know how to explain it - it &apos;s really unique .
my last stop is a business of saying that a new generation of record lovers should have inspired : urban Outfitters .
while I seem to mutate the jeans hotpants , I watch a group of young teenagers group up for a moment around Polaroid cameras before a father and his daughter consider buying a Crosley record player .
to the left is a stairwell , a wall full of plates from Adele , Jeff Buckley , Amy Winehouse and Fleetwood Mac : a mix of contemporary music and classics that feature essential plates for an average collection .
no one looks at them - perhaps because they &apos;re just purely decorative , some so far above that it &apos;s impossible to touch them .
it &apos;s pure &quot; record art . &quot;
but given that any attraction for these items means more money for the industry and some customers could send into the depths of sohos for more , there is nothing to complain about .
it &apos;s no surprise that a population group that has more time and money than others is also the one that spends most on luxury items like plates .
even though my research revealed that YouGov &apos;s results are true , they leave , at least in record stores in Soho , the large number of female collectors who exist in reality , record stores and online forums are not taken into account .
