military leadership falsifies ISIS intelligence , notes committee of Congress
military personnel from the United States Central Command changed intelligence to paint a more optimistic picture of the war against the so @-@ called Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than had allowed actual conditions on the ground , a committee of inquiry from Congress reported in a report Thursday .
the preliminary report , drawn up by a task force of Republican members of the force commander , intelligence commander and the military budget commander , reports of great dissatisfaction among Central Command intelligence analysts who reported how superiors changed their assessments of American efforts in the fight against the Islamic State .
the Central Command , briefly Cencom , is the military headquarters in Tampa , Florida , which controls U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia .
&quot; intelligence information typically disguised by senior CENTCOM commanders regularly recorded a more positive picture of American efforts to counter terrorism than had allowed actual conditions on the ground and were consistently more positive than analysis of other news services , &quot; a newspaper article quoted the report .
&quot; what happened at CENTCOM is unacceptable - our soldiers suffer when bad analyses are presented to our political leaders , &quot; noted Ken Calvert , Republican member of the House of Representatives .
the leadership errors in CENTCOM range to the top of the organization .
the 10 @-@ page report details persistent problems in 2014 and 2015 in descriptions and analyses of American efforts in training Iraqi forces .
although there is no direct evidence that government leaders under Obama have given instructions to change the reports , it shows how analysts have faced pressure from their presenters to draw a more optimistic picture of the Islamic State &apos;s threat , also known as ISIS or ISIL .
&quot; during the first half of 2015 , many Central Command press releases , opinions and statements before Congress were significantly more positive than the facts , &quot; the report noted .
for example , a CENTCOM member announced publicly that a military reconnaissance of Mossuls could begin in April or May 2015 .
Mossul , Iraq &apos;s second @-@ largest city , remains under the control of the Islamic State .
&quot; after months of investigation , so much is clear , &quot; Mike Pompeo , Republican congressman from Kansas , said in an opinion .
from mid @-@ 2014 to mid @-@ 2015 , the top Central Command officials changed intelligence reports to downplay the danger posed by ISIS in Iraq .
Republicans launched the task force after they admitted that analysts were worried about manipulating reports on the Islamic State .
the report published on Thursday will be supplemented by more detailed findings while the investigation continues .
in addition , further investigations into CENTCOM reports are under way by the Ministry of Defence &apos;s inspector general .
democratic members of the news center released their own findings on Thursday , consistent with some of the conclusions of the Republican Task Force .
&quot; in 2014 and 2015 , CENTCOM created an overly limited process for producing intelligence assessments on ISIL and Iraqi security services , &quot; the highest @-@ ranking Democrat in the Committee , member of the House of Representatives Adam B. Schiff , announced in an opinion .
that process , Mr. Schiff said , &quot; delayed the release of intelligence reports , &quot; damaging morale among analysts and &quot; gave unduly little room for dissent . &quot;
but Mr. Schiff and Democrats declined to find any evidence of White House intervention among CENTCOM analysts regarding a &quot; certain political opinion . &quot;
the preliminary results of the congressional investigation were published Tuesday by The Daily Beast .
last August , the New York Times reported investigations by the Pentagon &apos;s inspector general , which were recorded after complaints from CENTCOM analysts .
Lt. Cmdr. Patrick Evans , a Pentagon press secretary , admitted in an opinion that the Defense Department would not comment on reports from Congress while the inspector general &apos;s investigation was still under way .
but he also admitted that &quot; experts sometimes have very divergent opinions about the interpretation of complex data , and that news services and the Ministry of Defence welcome a controversial discussion of these important issues of national defense . &quot;
the investigation has had repercussions over the issue of a successful air campaign under American leadership in Iraq and Syria ( a claim now made by a growing number of Defense Department officials ) .
but last year &apos;s accusations raised questions about how President Obama can rely on the Central Command for honest assessments of military operations in Iraq , Afghanistan , Libya and other crisis regions .
the criticism of secret information about the Islamic State is reminiscent of the incidents of more than ten years ago , when a CENTCOM analyst , Gregory Hooker , summed up a document on how the then @-@ government under George W. Bush looked at only a small occupying force in Iraq , contrary to the recommendations of many analysts , and gave little time to the invasion in 2003 .
Mr. Hooker also played a key role in the uprising against current coverage of the Islamic State .
last year , the team around Mr. Hooker , according to government agencies , found that , contrary to the government &apos;s statements , air strikes against the refineries held by the Islamic State would not have a significant impact on the financial position of the terrorist group , as these provisional refineries would have been operational to sell oil on the black market .
however , that finding was not released , the Times reported in September .
Centcom &apos;s then @-@ commander , Gen. Lloyd J. Austin III , was criticised by members of the legislature for his overly positive assessment of the war situation at a hearing before the Senate .
general Austin retired in April and was replaced by Gen. Joseph L. Votel at Central Command .
