Greenland shark : the oldest vertebrate is nearly 400 years old
rare sight .
Greenland sharks usually come to the surface only in winter .
after an investigation on board the research vessel Sanna was allowed to return to the sea .
he was born in 1624 and swims with well over 1 km / h through the North Atlantic - to date .
Greenland sharks only get up to 150 years of offspring .
the Greenland shark lies along the coast of the North Atlantic , with an average of just 1,220 metres .
only when it arrives , the five @-@ metre long animal accelerates to a hefty 2.6 km / h - and is half as fast as a seal at this maximum speed .
however , this loneliness seems to be a recipe for a high age .
Julius Nielsen of the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues report in the journal Science at any rate a Greenland shark that could be 392 years old .
&quot; madness , &quot; notes Alexander Schoulein of the Max Planck Institute for demographics in Rostock this life span , which means a world record for vertebrates .
although the evolutionary biologist has long suspected that Greenland sharks will be stone @-@ painted .
only lacked the evidence .
Greenland sharks are difficult to observe , after all they live mainly in the Ice Sea off the sparsely populated coasts of Canada , Greenland , Norway and Spitsbergen .
because they prefer water temperatures around the six degrees Celsius , they usually appear on the surface only in winter .
researchers know little about Greenland &apos;s lifestyle .
her slow @-@ motion pace decreases her when she issued six animals with a transmitter in front of Spitsbergen .
prey do this sharks anyway : in the stomach of an animal , researchers found the remains of a seal , another had swallowed the jaw bone of a young polar bear .
they may hunt sleepy animals or patrol at the bottom of the iceberg and seek carcasses that torch down from higher water levels .
Julius Nielsen and his colleagues now looked at 28 Greenland sharks that caught fishermen in front of Greenland or Spitzbergen between 2010 and 2013 as by @-@ catch from the depths of the North Atlantic .
the smallest shark was just 81 inches long , while the largest 502 inches tall .
to determine the age of the animals , they analyzed with the carbon 14 method the lens core of the sharks .
this center of the eye lens is created even before the birth of the sharks , the proteins contained in it are no longer renewed .
the two smallest sharks had remarkably much carbon @-@ 14 in the lineman .
their birth should therefore be after the early 1960s , when nuclear weapons tests dragged larger amounts of this radioactive carbon into the atmosphere .
in the third @-@ smallest animal with 220 centimetres length , the lineman contained a small surplus of carbon 14 from the nuclear weapons tests , so it should have celebrated its 50th birthday in its investigation in 2012 .
all major Greenland sharks , on the other hand , had normal carbon @-@ 14 levels in their linemen , resulting from cosmic radiation in the atmosphere .
in fact , the carbon 2pm for a 493 centimetre long Greenland shark showed an age of 335 , while the record shark with 502 centimetres is likely to be even 392 years old .
that Greenland females only get offspring when they are longer than four metres was known .
now researchers of length were able to assign an age .
since one of the animals with 392 centimetres was probably on the threshold of gender maturity and its age was determined by 156 years , Greenland sharks can obviously be propagated at least one and a half centuries .
this , too , is likely to be world record for vertebrates .
that such methusaleme live mainly in icy waters is no coincidence .
even the previous record holder , a 211 @-@ year @-@ old Greenland whale , in whose bacon at the neck set a 120 @-@ year @-@ old harpoline , was caught in front of Alaska .
due to the low temperatures , the organism of the animals living there often runs on Sparflamme .
so they mature later - and aging slower .
in order to keep warm in cold water , the animals are also often particularly large .
because volume grows much faster than its surface through which the animal loses heat .
the loss of heat from a gram mouse is therefore much greater than a gram elephant .
another advantage : they have fewer enemies .
&quot; a smaller animal lives more dangerous and should focus on having as many offspring as possible as possible , &quot; explains the evolutionary biologist Schoulein .
a very large animal , on the other hand , should invest its resources more in a long life .
