Frankfurt benefits from Brexit
the city on the Main therefore has the best opportunities to attract jobs and firms from London in competition with Paris , Dublin and Luxembourg .
&quot; it is very likely that Frankfurt will benefit most from the Brexit vote , &quot; says Michael Voigtland , head of the IW &apos;s financial and real estate markets .
after the Brexit referendum , it is uncertain whether financial institutions can continue to operate from London through financial transactions across the EU .
for the so @-@ called EU passport , they have until now been authorised in the UK .
that is what big US banks are using .
several banks have already announced plans to shift jobs .
the &quot; Frankfurt Main Finance &quot; lobbying group expects 10000 new jobs on the Main within five years .
for Frankfurt , according to the IW , the seat of the European Central Bank ( ECB ) shares responsibility for monetary policy and supervision over the largest banks in the eurozone , as well as other important authorities such as EIOPA and the ESRB risk body .
while the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development ( OECD ) is headquartered in Paris , it is less important for the financial sector than the ECB .
&quot; the proximity to the central bank is important to banks as they can communicate so directly with oversight , &quot; says IW professor Voigtland .
Luxembourg is home to a large fund industry , but it is also worse off in infrastructure , as is Dublin .
Frankfurt is significantly easier to reach thanks to the major airport .
the city also has easy access to commercial properties .
&quot; in Paris , it &apos;s not so easy to find free high @-@ quality offices , &quot; Voigtland says .
on the Seine , rents for first @-@ class commercial properties are 50 % higher than on the Main .
Frankfurt also offers a higher quality of life than competition thanks to good medical care and infrastructure and less crime .
in a ranking of consultancy Mercer , the city is ranked seventh , Luxembourg at No. 19 , Dublin at No. 33 and Paris at 37th .
although quality of life is a matter of preferences : &quot; with its already strong position as a financial location for the European single market , Frankfurt could attract more banks and investors , &quot; the IW concluded .
London , however , will remain the most important financial centre in Europe , according to economic researchers .
for this , the balance of power also speaks : in London , around 144000 people worked in the banking sector according to national bank Helaba figures at the end of 2015 and 62500 in Frankfurt .
