Clinton earns 10.75 million in 2015 and pays 34.2 % federal tax
Hillary Clinton released her tax return for 2015 on Friday , which resulted in an income of USD 10.75 million for the Democratic presidential candidate and her husband , and an effective federal tax rate of 34.2 % .
in 2015 , the Clintons donated $ 1 million for charitable purposes , mainly to the Clinton Foundation ; former President Bill Clinton earned nearly $ 5.3 million in Redehonoraries ; the former secretary of state gave an income of $ 3 million from the publisher Simon &amp; Schuster for her book on her tenure in the State Department .
Clinton &apos;s nominee for the vice @-@ president , Senator Tim Kaine from Virginia , disclosed his tax returns , along with his wife Anne Holton .
they paid an effective federal tax rate of 20.3 % in 2015 .
&quot; Hillary Clinton and Tim Kaine continue to set standards in terms of financial transparency , &quot; Clinton campaign hero Jennifer Palmieri announced in an opinion .
in a stark contrast , Donald Trump hides behind false excuses and backers about his past promises to publish his tax returns .
it is common for U.S. presidential candidates to publish their tax returns , although they are not required by law because of that .
Trump , a New York businessman , and his lawyers have indicated a tax review by tax authorities as a reason for his refusal .
&quot; they &apos;re on the train , &quot; Clinton campaign aide Ian Sams wrote on Twitter , referring to the publication of the Democrats &apos; presidential candidate .
on Thursday , Michael Cohen , Trump &apos;s special adviser , told CNN that he would not allow Trump to publish something before the tax audits are not complete .
Trump &apos;s critics , including the 2012 Republican presidential nominee , Mitt Romney , have already said that his refusal raises questions about assets , his donations to charitable organizations , his business interests and various other links , particularly with Russia .
Clinton has already plunged to the issue and released a video on the Internet on Friday in which senior Republican Trump is calling for his tax returns to be published .
on Thursday , she also addressed the issue during a speech on the economy in Michigan .
&quot; he refuses to do what any other presidential candidate has done in recent decades and to publish his tax returns , &quot; she said to the crowd .
politico has reported that Trump did not pay or very little tax during the 1990s for two years , and an economics journalist at the New York Times quoted a number of tax lawyers and tax advisers on Friday as saying that could still be the case .
Federal taxes have become an issue in the campaign .
Clinton supports a scheme named after the billionaire and investor Warren Buffett , which would ensure that people who earn more than $ 1 million pay a tax rate of at least 30 % .
President Obama also supports the proposal .
during a campaign event for Hillary Clinton last week in Omaha , Nebraska , Buffett , whose Berkshire Hathaway industrial conglomerate is based here , called Trump for a meeting to exchange their tax returns .
Buffett said he had also undergone a tax review of the IRS and Trump was &quot; afraid &quot; of voters rather than tax authorities .
Clinton &apos;s campaign has released tax returns back to 2007 .
the Clintons , who now live in Chappaqua , New York , paid an effective federal tax rate of about 32 % between 2007 and 2014 and an effective combined tax rate of about 40.5 % .
the 2011 Clinton tax returns showed that they paid only USD 100 of their income , unlike most Americans .
their main asset was a low @-@ cost index fund from which the Clinton dividends and yields of USD 109,000 .
