future of the melting of Portland due to the lifting of the energy contract
the future of Portland &apos;s aluminium melting in Victoria - as well as hundreds of jobs from workers - is at stake as the plant operator will terminate the energy supply contract , thereby lifting all supply contracts , as the supplier of energy .
that move followed the government &apos;s decision in Victoria earlier this year not to grant further subsidies to operate the plant .
a 20 @-@ year subsidy expires in November .
up to 2000 jobs at the Alcoa plant in Portland are at stake .
no fewer than 2,000 jobs - direct and indirect - could be at risk of closure .
moreover , domino effects could occur as melting consumes around 10 percent of Victorias &apos; total power generation .
in 2014 , Alcoa closed the Point Henry meltdown , leading to a closure of the Anglesea power plant last year .
Alcoa &apos;s meltdown in Portland is losing money and risking closure .
this move follows years of speculation about the future of the plant , originally as a result of the strong Australian dollar and most recently due to the electricity price for the plant .
AGL , which supplies the large aluminium smelting with its Loy Yang A power plant in Latrobe Valley , announced that it expects three other owners to terminate their contracts .
the facility is majority owned by a joint venture of Alcoa and Alumina , of which Chinese company CITIC and Japanese Marubeni Corp hold smaller shares .
&quot; AGL assumes that the plant will continue to operate in Portland , which means further physical demand for electricity through melting , &quot; the company said .
AGL continued to say that the contracts were so @-@ called &quot; security deals &quot; that should have come into effect from November 2016 .
the contracts have a 12 @-@ month termination period so they will end in 2017 .
&quot; from that point of view , AGL assumes that contracts will contribute 17 to revenue in the fiscal year , &quot; the power supplier said .
all potential impacts on revenue on AGL from GJ 18 are currently limited by the forecasts of strong futures markets for wholesale electricity prices .
AGL announced that it had already written off the value of the contracts in its annual deal of $ 187 million in &quot; anticipation of termination . &quot;
Alcoa said that the decision to book out the contracts did not affect Alcoas &quot; ability to operate the meltdown or to ensure the power supply to the meltdown . &quot;
the US company said it had concluded a 20 @-@ year contract with Loy Yang in 2010 , which should have entered into force from November this year , even though it is still guilty of a statement as to why it resigned from the contract .
analysts warn about the industry &apos;s poor economic conditions ahead of the possible closure of the Portland meltdown in Victoria and the Tomago plant near Newcastle .
referring to the analyst &apos;s statements earlier this week , Head of Operations Stephen Mikkelsen said Portland consume about 600 megawatts and tomago about 900 megawatts of electricity each year .
should both plants disappear from the market , this would mean a significant reduction in demand in the &#91; electricity market &#93; .
and for us as a power generator , that wouldn &apos;t be good , &quot; he said .
