local council centers dismiss 160,000 people a year
more than 160,000 of the country &apos;s needs for assistance are dismissed annually by local council centres , while the industry is grappling with the impact of further cuts on already overloaded transactions .
in Queensland , three out of five people - mostly older people , immigrants , vulnerable workers , victims of violence and those with no resources for unjust dolphins and the like - are already being dismissed in their search for free legal advice and legal assistance .
legal services from the community , which are already overly outlawed , are preparing for further cuts .
as of June next year , these legal centres will lose another 30 percent of their federal funds .
the director of Queesland &apos;s community centers James Farrell said the latest survey by the National Association of Local Government Centres showed that thousands of people are already being turned away every year .
Farrell said the situation would only get worse without a repeal of the federal government &apos;s decision .
&quot; Queensland council centers are chronically underfunded , meaning thousands of people are turned away from important services you need , &quot; he said .
people who leave violent relationships , people with unmanageable and crushing debts , families who go through divisions , workers who have been unfairly sacked - all of these people have problems of a legal nature and this survey shows they cannot get the help they need .
the federal government will cut funds by 30 percent from June 2017 , meaning that thousands of vulnerable people from Queensland will be forced to cope with their legal problems without any help .
