Nokia 9000 Communicator : the first smartphone
e @-@ mail and Internet in slow motion : 20 years ago , the Nokia Communicator came onto the market .
the successors dominate the world today - his manufacturer experienced a disaster .
the device weighed nearly half a kilogram and was more than four times as heavy as an iPhone 5 .
it was thicker and bigger , so it wasn &apos;t good in hand .
on the contrary , it was pretty knocking .
built @-@ in memory was initially eight megabytes , which would now range for about two selfies with high resolution .
an iPhone is now delivered with at least 16 gigabytes .
the &quot; Nokia 9000 Communicator &quot; came into business exactly 20 years ago , on August 15 , 1996 - and it was the first smartphone .
for a few euros , lovers can still buy the equipment on the Internet , but they somehow come from the stone age of the Internet age .
20 years ago , however , the Communicator was a sensation .
the Finnish mobile phone manufacturer had announced the product a few months earlier at the Cebit computer fair in Hanover as an &quot; office in the West End format . &quot;
in fact , the new mobile phone was able to reach a lot for then standards : SMS and e @-@ mails could be sent and received , even by fax was the Communicator to reach .
even access to websites was possible via HTML browser , albeit agonizing slowly .
a calculator was available , a digital address book and an electronic calendar .
there was a small antenna , and the phone could be turned up similar to a laptop .
then found a small keyboard and a black and white screen .
quite proud was the price : 2700 D @-@ Mark , that &apos;s about 1400 euros .
the average selling price of a smartphone in Germany was â¬ 392 in 2015 .
no one could expect the Communicator to become the start of the smartphone era in August 1996 .
since then , everything has been different .
smart phones are a success story , though not for Nokia .
the Finn mobile phone division experienced an unprecedented disaster , eventually sold and handled to Microsoft .
the market dominates today , all of which came much later than Nokia .
always and everywhere online , that &apos;s today for a lot of people everyday .
in 2015 , there were nearly two billion smartphone users worldwide .
about 1.4 billion devices were sold , with Samsung and Apple alone accounting for 555 million pieces .
worldwide sales of devices are around 400 billion euros .
this includes the well @-@ running operations of the countless app providers and telecommunications companies .
around the smartphone , an entire industry has now emerged .
the crucial breakthrough to the mass market came only in early 2007 , then Apple chief executive Steve Jobs on the Mac World announced the launch of the iPhones .
he promised three devices in one : a music player , a phone and an Internet communicator , to use everything easily by touch screen .
Apple &apos;s winning streak began , yet today the iPhone is the group &apos;s most important product .
Nokia , Motorola and Blackberry , which dominated the market , had the afterthought .
they eventually disappeared , Blackberry has struggled .
the shots now have Apple and Asian suppliers like Samsung .
the smartphone is a self @-@ evident 20 years after its invention .
on average , every German now looks on his mobile 88 times a day .
&quot; we all need to learn to get rid of the smartphone , &quot; said just Janina Kugel , on the Siemens board of staff .
permanent accessibility is now considered a curse and blessing at the same time .
