Kepler measures rotation rate of stars in star running of plejads
the latest mission with the Kepler space telescope has helped astronomers gather the most complete catalog of rotation rates among the stars of the Plejaden &apos;s star home .
the new data will help astronomers understand why stars rotate at different rates in the startup and in what context the rotation periods are related to planetary development .
&quot; we hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters , we learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star , his age and even the history of his solar system , &quot; Luisa Rebull , a researcher at Caltech &apos;s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena , said in a news release .
the chapel of the Plejaden is 445 light years from Earth .
many stars in this star shop , which was created about 125 million years ago , now reach adulthood .
they are now turning fastest .
at peak rotational rates , these mature stars have large amounts of star winds .
as these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars , they have a slowing effect on the stars .
when a star is ageing , his rotation rate begins to slow .
Kepler measures each star &apos;s rotation rate by recognizing the time between the appearance of a recognizable star fleece -- like sunflecks .
the latest catalogue of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars are turning more slowly than fewer massive stars .
Rebull compares the stars with dancers , with larger stars turning slower pirouettes than smaller ones .
&quot; in the &quot; Ballet &quot; of the Plejaden , we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive , whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars , &quot; Rebull said .
since the plot &apos;s startup is so close , it serves as an ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities like rotation rates .
&quot; the star bunch of the Plejaden offers an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions , younger and older , &quot; Rebull said .
there is still much ahead of us about what we would like to know more about how the How , When and Why Stars slow down their rotation rates and hang up their &quot; dance shoes . &quot;
Rebull and her colleagues have detailed in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the plejads &apos; rotation rates , which will soon appear in the Astronomical Journal .
