data feud : so perfide hackers their ransom
programmers of extortion malware are currently targeting companies - and are successful .
according to a recent survey by malware defense specialists Malwarebytes among 540 companies in North America , the UK and Germany , 40 percent of companies surveyed have been killed at least once in the past 12 months , in part several times by an attack involving blackmail software .
in Germany , almost 20 percent of companies were already the target of a Ransomware blackmail .
forty per cent of victims willingly paid the ransom demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to reuse the systems and data that were being accessed .
offenders specialize in their blackmail software , according to Malwarebytes &apos; observations , to attacks on corporate networks .
if they are successful there , the potentially extortionable ransom is significantly higher than for private users .
&quot; we are currently seeing a terrifying rapid evolution of malicious software , &quot; Malwarebytes chief executive Marcin Kleczynski explains in conversation with the &quot; world . &quot;
in 2008 , most malware programs were still designed to send advertising .
then the perpetrators discovered blackmail software for themselves .
first , private users were the target , but the switch to corporate attacks took place alarmingly quickly in recent months .
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern : once active on a victim &apos;s computer , it searches for recently changed files such as Word , Excel or database files , and archives of images and videos .
these files encrypt the Ransomware and solves the originals sustainably .
the software then presents the demands of the blacksmith .
to get the end key code to the files , victims must transfer money - mostly in the form of cryptocurrency Bitcoin .
but where private users are at stake the personal photo database , companies are concerned about sensitive customer data or project databases without which production is shut down .
accordingly , the damage will be higher if a Ransomware fails .
twenty @-@ one percent of the German firms affected reported revenue losses from Ransomware , while 13 percent even had to cut business completely , in one case people were in danger of living .
in Germany , hospitals have already been victims of attacks , whose patients may be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records .
&quot; we always tell the victims : don &apos;t pay , you just promote the problem , &quot; Kleczynski explains .
but 80 to 90 percent of companies that pay get their data back .
for managers , it is difficult to reject offenders &apos; demand in the face of deadlock in operation .
the hackers , in turn , know that and try everything to build a good reputation .
in a recent study , F @-@ Secure &apos;s security researchers looked at the user &apos;s areas and contact with the expressors and come to the conclusion : offenders are actually trying to build some kind of customer service to take more money .
they explain to their victims via chat how to pay by Bitcoin , create freely accessible support websites or decrypt example files in vain .
and if private people are replaced after payments of a few hundred euros , companies will have to negotiate hard and pay five @-@ digit sums to get their data back unencrypted .
given the potentially high and relatively risky gains from Ransomware blackmail , the hackers become more professional and share the work , says security expert Chester Wisniewski of the antivirus provider Sophos : &quot; a single person can write a Ransomware about a week . &quot;
more likely , however , is that it is three or four people .
the programmers then sell their malicious software in the form of a software building kit to the actual blacksmith .
the previous malware kits were created by buying the malware itself , consulting and additional tools for a one @-@ off , fixed price between $ 1,000 and $ 10,000 .
&quot; included in the delivery range is an adjustment tool , so smaller configurations , appearance and branding can be changed , &quot; says Wisniewski .
the blacksmiths then seek more hackers to spread the freshly bought software among the victims .
we live in a service economy .
so you log in to one of the forums underground , buy the set from a criminal and then hire another to install the software on as many PCs as possible .
payment is made per infected computer .
&quot; usually the criminals then instruct Spammer with the spread , &quot; Wisniewski explains .
Ransomware &apos;s risk is now well known to many companies that better secure their data .
more than 50 percent of corporate IT executives in the Malwarebytes survey trust to be able to fend off Ransomware using file @-@ back and scanning software .
accordingly , the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies .
&quot; if the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful erasing , the offenders will instead face the release of sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations , &quot; explains Malwarebytes chief executive Marcin Kleczynski .
as a result , the loss potential is much higher than before depending on the type of data .
in the future , the perpetrators could also set completely new targets on the Internet of Things .
at the hacking conference Defcon , security researchers demonstrated how they could get a thermostat associated with the Internet under their control .
in the middle of winter , the release of such a blocked heating could well be worth a ransom .
if the offenders then block an entire manufacturing road in a factory instead of heating , Ransomware could also become an issue in industry 4.0 .
